@article{Ryan2016,
   abstract = {Design in Familiar Places incorporates the findings of Brower's fifteen years of field studies in several Balti-more urban neighborhoods to demonstrate the importance residents' perceptions and behavioral tendencies can have on design and redevelopment of urban residential environments. Brower's primary aim is to make planners and designers aware of what he has learned about how residents see their familiar world of home in fundamentally different ways from designers and what this means to successful physical planning. To do so, he weaves a skillful story of applied research, literature review and his own thinking leading to the conclusion that \&dquo;to create good housing we must create places that people care about and that satisfy their need for familiar surroundings\&dquo; (p. xv). The author, a former practitioner turned academic, has an obviously rich storehouse of experience and observations from which he draws. Most of his studies were done for the Baltimore City Department of Planning, directed by Larry Reich while Brower was Chief of Comprehensive Planning and Chief of Design Analysis. Some readers may recognize material in various sections of the book that has appeared previously in environmental literature. Brower acknowledges the influence of Appleyard and Lynch on his work, and it is likely both leaders in the process-oriented school of urban design and planning would have approved of Brower's resulting volume, especially as an example of research informing practice. The book is organized into two parts. Brower begins by laying the groundwork of broad ideas about behavior and perception of place; familiarity, satisfaction, and characteristics of home environments; and the theory and process of design itself. In Part 1, the first chapter is devoted to three modes of perception-responsive, operational, and inferen-tial-and how differences in point of view can and should influence design response. Brower then draws upon the work of, among others, Fried, Lynch, Winkel, Appleyard, Rapoport, and Lansing and Marans, as well as his own studies in Baltimore, to carefully review how residents define and judge their home environment. The third chapter recognizes the different priorities of residents and outsiders in evaluating the environment, with Brower noting it is possible for both to find satisfaction in the same place. Brower presents his study in which residents and designers each look at photographs of the built environment to show how designers commonly focus on physical proportions and patterns while residents (nondesigners) attend more to what they can read into the surface qualities of a place. In the fifth chapter, Brower builds on several more Baltimore studies to argue for two roles in design and planning: (1) expert, acting on behalf of others, to come up with ideas and solutions; and (2) facilitator, helping others define and resolve their own problems. In his wrap-up chapter of theory and practice, he exhorts those working on housing design in high-threat urban areas to see the place the way the residents do-\&dquo;as a cabin in the wilderness (not a cottage in the country)\&dquo; and design for an appropriate refuge. Part 2 is Brower's research cache of case studies to provide the resident's-eye view of Harlem Park, a predominantly black, low-income neighborhood in Balti-more. One of the city's earliest renewal projects, it consists of thirty-two residential blocks, twenty-nine of which had inner-block parks created during the 1960s. Brower's thirteen years of research in Harlem Park included techniques such as interviews, observations, person counts, doll-play games with children, and interventions. Chapter nine is a delightful and insightful collection of transcripts, letters, and staff notes about several experiments connected with the mid-block parks, including design, management, and involvement. He follows this with a summary chapter, \&dquo;As Residents See It;' including views on streetfronts, back spaces, parks, near-home spaces, and community responsibilities. Some readers, anxious for the bottom line of how to make good residential environments that work well and are cared for, may turn first to the final chapter. There they will find the author's design guidelines. Practitioners and policy-makers will find Brower's thirteen design guidelines easily accessible and to the point. Those who have enjoyed the case material effectively presented in the previous chapters will find no surprises. Brower has earned the right to make these summary \&dquo;should\&dquo; statements. These summary statements deal primarily with the design of street space in high-density urban neighborhoods : let the residents keep it lively and well-used; let them watch it, own it, manage it, use it as recreational as well as circulation space; and, above all, let the residents make the design decisions.},
